\section{Empirical Evaluations}
\label{sec:evaluation}

We evaluate DeXposure-FM as a foundation model for decentralized credit-exposure networks along three complementary axes: (i) \textit{multi-step forecasting} of edge-level exposures and network-level statistics, (ii) \textit{policy-relevant scenario analysis} that generates shock-consistent paths of losses and contagion under major stress events, and (iii) \textit{imputation and denoising} of missing/noisy exposures and TVL histories, including downstream gains on forecasting and link-prediction.

\subsection{Rolling-based Training and Evaluation}\label{subsec:rolling}

Let $\mathbf{E}_t \in \mathbb{R}_{+}^{N\times N}$ denote the directed exposure matrix at time $t$, where $(\mathbf{E}_t)_{ij}$ is the exposure of $i$ to $j$, and let $\mathbf{x}_t$ collect node- and protocol-level covariates (e.g., TVL, yields, sector tags). We adopt a \textit{time-based rolling-origin} evaluation scheme (walk-forward validation): for each forecasting origin $\tau$ we train on $\{1,\dots,\tau\}$ and evaluate on $\{\tau+1,\dots,\tau+H\}$, rolling $\tau$ forward on a fixed stride. This aligns with standard out-of-sample forecast evaluation in time series \cite{Tashman2000,HyndmanAthanasopoulos2021}. We report results under both (a) \textit{expanding windows} and (b) \textit{fixed-length sliding windows} to assess robustness to regime shifts.

For each metric we report the mean and dispersion across origins (e.g., mean$\pm$sd). When comparing two forecasters, we assess statistical significance using loss-differential tests following \cite{DieboldMariano1995} with horizon-specific losses.

\subsection{Task I: Multi-step Forecasting}\label{subsec:forecast}

\paragraph{Targets.}
We evaluate forecasts at horizons $h\in\{1,3,7,14\}$ (or matched to the dataset frequency) for:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Edge-level exposures:} $\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{t+h}$.
  \item \textbf{Node-level aggregates:} out-/in-exposure vectors $\mathbf{e}^{\text{out}}_t=\mathbf{E}_t\mathbf{1}$ and $\mathbf{e}^{\text{in}}_t=\mathbf{E}_t^\top\mathbf{1}$.
  \item \textbf{Network-level statistics:} density, weighted density, concentration (e.g., exposure HHI), and sector connectivity (e.g., sector-by-sector exposure blocks).
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Metrics (point forecasts).}
We report MAE, RMSE, and (where well-defined) MAPE. To reflect economic materiality, we additionally report TVL- or exposure-weighted errors:
\[
\mathrm{WMAE}=\frac{\sum_{i,j} w_{ij,t}\,\lvert (\widehat{\mathbf{E}}_{t+h})_{ij}-(\mathbf{E}_{t+h})_{ij}\rvert}{\sum_{i,j} w_{ij,t}},\quad
w_{ij,t}\propto \mathrm{TVL}_{i,t}\ \text{or}\ (\mathbf{E}_{t})_{ij}.
\]
We also report tail-focused metrics (e.g., top-$k$ edges by realized exposure) and directional accuracy (sign of change) for node-level aggregates.

\paragraph{Distributional and structural fidelity.}
Since exposures are heavy-tailed and network structure is central, we report (i) rank correlations of edge weights, (ii) errors on network statistics (e.g., HHI, density), and (iii) distributional distances between predicted and realized exposure-weight distributions (e.g., Wasserstein distance on $\log(1+E)$). For sector connectivity we report block-wise errors and topological stability of the sector graph.

\paragraph{Baselines.}
We compare against a broad set of classical and modern baselines:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Na\"ive} (persistence / random-walk) forecasts.
  \item \textbf{ARIMA}-family univariate forecasts \cite{BoxJenkins1970}.
  \item \textbf{VAR / SVAR} baselines on aggregated series and low-dimensional summaries \cite{Sims1980,Lutkepohl2005}.
  \item \textbf{Dynamic factor / diffusion-index} forecasting using principal components \cite{StockWatson2002}.
  \item \textbf{Low-rank tensor/matrix forecasting} (dynamic matrix factorization; nuclear-norm regularization) \cite{Mazumder2010}.
  \item \textbf{Temporal graph neural networks} for dynamic graphs, including TGAT, TGN and DySAT variants \cite{Xu2020TGAT,Rossi2020TGN,Sankar2020DySAT}.
\end{itemize}
All baselines use the same rolling-origin splits and are tuned on a validation segment inside each training window (or using nested rolling evaluation when feasible).

\subsection{Task II: Policy-relevant Scenario Analysis}\label{subsec:scenario}

\paragraph{Scenario design.}
We evaluate the model's ability to generate \textit{shock-consistent} counterfactual trajectories under targeted stress events:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Stablecoin de-peg}: impose an exogenous price/peg shock and liquidity outflow pattern; propagate to protocols with stablecoin collateral and LP exposure.
  \item \textbf{Exchange failure / large entity default}: impose a default or withdrawal shock on a major hub; model contagion through direct exposures and shared liquidity.
\end{enumerate}
Scenarios are implemented as interventions on observed covariates (e.g., TVL, prices, volumes) and/or constraints on subsets of edges and node states, holding other exogenous series fixed.

\paragraph{Evaluation criteria.}
Because scenarios are counterfactual, we evaluate along three dimensions:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Historical backtesting (event studies):} for stress events observed in the sample, condition on pre-event history and compare generated trajectories to realized outcomes (losses, TVL drawdowns, exposure rewiring).
  \item \textbf{Internal consistency:} non-negativity, no-arbitrage style constraints where applicable, conservation rules for accounting identities, and monotone relations under larger shocks.
  \item \textbf{Contagion realism:} timing and localization of stress (which sectors and hubs are hit first), severity (peak-to-trough drawdown, cumulative losses), and breadth (fraction of nodes affected).
\end{itemize}
We summarize outcomes with interpretable indicators (e.g., peak drawdown of total TVL, time-to-peak-loss, fraction of protocols experiencing $>x\%$ drawdown) and compare to simplified contagion baselines inspired by systemic risk literature \cite{Acemoglu2013,Glasserman2016}.

\subsection{Task III: Imputation and Denoising}\label{subsec:imputation}

\paragraph{Missingness and corruption regimes.}
We evaluate robustness under multiple regimes: (i) MCAR masking (random entries), (ii) block missingness (contiguous time gaps), and (iii) MNAR-like masking correlated with liquidity or stress (harder, policy-relevant). For denoising, we add controlled corruption (spikes, level shifts, and multiplicative noise) to exposures/TVL.

\paragraph{Reconstruction metrics.}
We compute MAE/RMSE on held-out entries and TVL-weighted variants (to prioritize economically material errors). We also report calibration diagnostics on reconstructed distributions (e.g., matching of heavy-tail behavior).

\paragraph{Downstream utility.}
To avoid optimizing solely for reconstruction, we measure downstream gains: (i) forecasting performance using imputed inputs, and (ii) link prediction quality (AUC, average precision) on edges whose existence/weight crosses economically meaningful thresholds. We report the \textit{delta} versus baselines, isolating the effect of imputation quality on downstream tasks.

\paragraph{Imputation baselines.}
We compare against forward-fill / interpolation, KNN-style imputation, and low-rank matrix completion (Soft-Impute / nuclear norm) \cite{Mazumder2010} as well as temporal GNN-based imputers \cite{Rossi2020TGN,Xu2020TGAT}.

\subsection{Ablations, Sensitivity, and Scalability}\label{subsec:ablations}

\paragraph{Ablations.}
We report ablations that isolate model components and modalities:
(i) time-series only vs.\ time-series+graph,
(ii) removing tabular covariates (TVL/sector tags),
(iii) removing cross-asset conditioning,
(iv) varying context length and prediction head, and
(v) masking strategies during pretraining.

\paragraph{Generalization checks.}
We evaluate transfer across sub-networks (e.g., sectors, protocol families) and across regimes (stable vs.\ stress periods) by stratifying rolling windows and reporting performance dispersion.

\paragraph{Efficiency.}
We report training and inference cost (wall-clock, memory) as a function of $N$, number of edges, and sequence length, and we include throughput under batched inference for scenario simulation.
